      "id": 359643,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Evidence for restricted rotation around amide <span data-math=\"{\\rm O}\\text{═}{\\rm C}\\text{–}{\\rm N}\"></span> bonds comes from NMR studies. At room temperature, the <sup>1</sup>H NMR spectrum of <i>N</i>,<i>N</i>-dimethylformamide shows three peaks: 2.9 <i>δ</i> (singlet, 3 H), 3.0 <i>δ</i> (singlet, 3 H), and 8.0 <i>δ</i> (singlet, 1 H). As the temperature is raised, however, the two singlets at 2.9 <i>δ</i> and 3.0 <i>δ</i> slowly merge. At 180 °C, the <sup>1</sup>H NMR spectrum shows only two peaks: 2.95 <i>δ</i> (singlet, 6 H) and 8.0 <i>δ</i> (singlet, 1 H). Explain this temperature-dependent behavior.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBcndaIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--3f832e22a35df67719ec899f62a970b8b44391f0/OChem_26_EC_020.jpg\" alt=\"The structure of N,N-dimethylformamide, an aldehyde group linked to a nitrogen atom to two methyl groups.\">",
